The previous Wrappin fix stopped the reported bug with one hard-coded code-token guard, but that was still too narrow to be the stable policy. This commit upgrades inheritance to a cheap local classifier. Each parsed row now carries a small lexical profile (word count, punctuation count, closer/brace/semicolon/operator/member-access flags). Inheritance decisions score continuation evidence against code evidence on the first selected row and then bias that result with one nearby nonblank row from the rest of the selection or the immediate trailing context.

The important policy split is asymmetric: comment inheritance is the dangerous case because it injects visible `//` markers, so it now requires continuation evidence to clear a higher bar than plain hanging-indent inheritance. Non-comment inherited schema still works for lists and prose continuations, but comment inheritance only wins when the text really looks like continuation prose or the nearby context strongly reinforces it. Low-confidence cases fall back to plain wrapping instead of transforming code into comments.

